                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18430227-1063-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430227-1063-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430227-1063-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="fraud"></interp> for obtaining goods by false pretences.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1277" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1277" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1277" type="surname" value="MORGAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1277" type="given" value="WILLIAM HENRY"></interp>WILLIAM HENRY MORGAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am warehouseman to Benjamin Wilmott Gabriel, of Watling-street. On the 21st of Jan. the prisoner called there—he said, "How is Mr. Gabriel?"—I said, "Pretty well"—He then said, "I want two dozen pairs of stockings for Mr. Moses Nathan"—I gave them to him—I should not hare given them to him if he had not said he came for them for Mr. Moses Nathan—I gave him a receipt, which he signed—I have it here.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1278" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1278" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1278" type="surname" value="NATHAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1278" type="given" value="MOSES"></interp>MOSES NATHAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a tailor, and live in Ratcliffe-highway. The pri<lb></lb>soner was in my service about ten months ago, but not in Jan.—I did not send him on the 21st of Jan. to Mr. Gabriel's for any stockings—I did not authorize him to take any from there, or to get any either then or at any other time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1279" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1279" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1279" type="surname" value="SAUNDERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1279" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM SAUNDERS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a hatter, and live in Shadwell. Between eight and nine o'clock on the 3rd of Feb. the prisoner came to my shop—he said he came for a hat or two for Mr. Lee, naming the size, and saying it was for the mate of a ship—in consequence of his stating he came from Mr. Lee, I gave him two hats—Lee was a customer of mine, and believing the prisoner came from him, I gave him the hats, which I would not have done otherwise.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430227-name-1280" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1280" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1280" type="surname" value="LEE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430227-name-1280" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN LEE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a tailor and outfitter, and live in High-street, Shadwell. I did not send the prisoner on the 3rd of Feb. to Mr. Saunders for hats—he was not in my service at that time, nor did I receive any.</p>
